{{no footnotes|date=November 2017}}
'''Jens Kraft''' (1720–1756) was a [[Danish people|Danish]] [[mathematics|mathematician]] and [[philosopher]] of [[Norwegian people|Norwegian]] birth. He was born in [[Frederikshald]] in [[Norway]], but at age 5 he became an orphan and was subsequently raised by his uncle in [[Thy (district)|Thy]] in [[Jutland]]. As a philosopher he introduced the study of [[ontology]] to [[Scandinavia]]n academic circles.

He was influenced by [[Christian Wolff (philosopher)|Christian Wolff]] whilst still a student at [[Copenhagen]], attending a lecture by Wolff while visiting [[University of Halle-Wittenberg|Halle]]. He was appointed professor of philosophy at the [[Sorø Academy]], where he responded to [[Alexander Gottlieb Baumgarten|Baumgarten]]'s ''Metaphsica'' with his own text ''metaphysik''. Both divided their work into ''[[cosmology|cosmologie]]'', ''[[ontology|ontologie]]'', ''[[psychology|psykologie]]'' and ''[[natural theology|naturlig theologie]]''.

Kraft made a distinction between [[time]] and [[eternity]] writing that "the finite can never obtain eternity, but it can obtain an infinite time, (Aevum) or a time with beginning but without end." The infinite by contrast has permanence (''sempiternité'')".

